1. What is Batch Apex?
Imagine your company has 8 million Accounts.
Your manager says:
Update all Accounts where Industry = 'Technology' and set Rating = 'Hot'.

If you write

List<Account> accs = [SELECT Id, Rating FROM Account];
for(Account a : accs){
    a.Rating='Hot';
}

update accs;

Salesforce will throw
-> Too many query rows: 50001

because Apex can only query 50,000 records synchronously.

Even if it somehow queried them,
Too many DML rows:10001

because one transaction can update only 10,000 records.

Salesforce says "Don't process millions of records in one transaction."
Instead, Break them into smaller transactions.

That's exactly what Batch Apex does.

================================================================================

2. What is Batch Apex doing internally?

Suppose you have 5,000 Accounts

Batch size = 200
Salesforce automatically divides them like this

Transaction 1
-------------
Account 1-200

Transaction 2
-------------
201-400

Transaction 3
-------------
401-600

...

Transaction 25
--------------
4801-5000

Each transaction has its own governor limits.

That's the biggest advantage.

================================================================================

3. Why Batch Apex?

Suppose 5000 Accounts

Without Batch 

One Transaction 5000 Updates, Governor Limits Shared

With Batch

25 Transactions, Each transaction gets
100 SOQL
150 DML
10,000 DML rows
60 sec CPU

again and again

That's why Batch can process millions of records.

================================================================================

