===========================================
Why do we use "global" in a Batch Apex Class?
===========================================

1. First, understand the access modifiers

private
-------
- Accessible only within the same class.
- Cannot be accessed by other classes.

Example:
private Integer count;

---------------------------------------------------------

public
------
- Accessible within the same namespace.
- Can be used by other Apex classes in the same org/package.
- Cannot be accessed outside a managed package.

Example:
public class AccountService {
}

---------------------------------------------------------

protected
---------
- Accessible within the same class and its subclasses.
- Mainly used for inheritance.

Example:
protected void processData() {
}

---------------------------------------------------------

global
------
- Highest level of access.
- Accessible from any Apex code.
- Accessible outside a managed package.
- Required when a class or method needs to be exposed externally.

Example:
global class AccountBatch {
}

===========================================================
Why do most Batch Apex examples use "global"?
===========================================================

A Batch Apex class implements the Database.Batchable interface.

Example:

global class AccountBatch implements Database.Batchable<SObject>

Historically, Salesforce documentation used "global" because Batch Apex classes
were commonly designed to be reusable and accessible from anywhere, including
managed packages.

However, in a normal Salesforce org (not a managed package), a Batch Apex class
does NOT have to be global.

You can write:

public class AccountBatch implements Database.Batchable<SObject>

and it works perfectly.

===========================================================
When should I use "public"?
===========================================================

Use "public" if:

- Your org is not a managed package.
- The batch class is used only inside your org.
- No external package needs access.

Example:

public class AccountBatch implements Database.Batchable<SObject> {

    public Database.QueryLocator start(Database.BatchableContext bc){
        ...
    }

    public void execute(Database.BatchableContext bc, List<Account> scope){
        ...
    }

    public void finish(Database.BatchableContext bc){
        ...
    }
}

This is the recommended approach for most projects.

===========================================================
When should I use "global"?
===========================================================

Use "global" only when:

1. You're developing a Managed Package.
2. Other orgs need to access your class.
3. The class is part of a public API.
4. Salesforce requires the class to be globally visible for package consumers.

Example:

global class AccountBatch implements Database.Batchable<SObject> {
}

===========================================================
Why NOT use global unnecessarily?
===========================================================

1. It exposes your class more than necessary.
2. Once released in a managed package, changing or removing global members is
   highly restricted because other orgs may depend on them.
3. It breaks the principle of least privilege.
4. It increases long-term maintenance complexity.

Rule:
Give only the minimum access required.

===========================================================
Batch Class Access Modifier Summary
===========================================================

private
- Cannot be used for a Batch class because Database.executeBatch() from another
  class cannot access it.

protected
- Not suitable for a top-level Batch class.
- Mainly intended for inherited members.

public
- Recommended for almost all Batch classes in normal Salesforce orgs.
- Accessible throughout your org.

global
- Use only for Managed Packages or when external access is required.

===========================================================
Comparison
===========================================================

Access Modifier    Same Class   Same Org   Managed Package Consumer
-------------------------------------------------------------------
private               Yes          No                No
protected             Yes      Limited*              No
public                Yes         Yes                No
global                Yes         Yes               Yes

*Protected is available within subclasses (and package context where applicable).

===========================================================
Interview Question
===========================================================

Q: Why do many Batch Apex examples use "global"?

Answer:

Most Salesforce examples use "global" because they are written to be compatible
with managed packages and external access. In a normal Salesforce org, "public"
is sufficient for Batch Apex. Use "global" only when your class must be exposed
outside the package or org.

===========================================================
Best Practice
===========================================================

Normal Salesforce Org
---------------------
public class AccountBatch implements Database.Batchable<SObject>

Managed Package
---------------
global class AccountBatch implements Database.Batchable<SObject>

Always choose the least permissive access modifier that satisfies your
requirement.
